While Jessica posted on social media every day, before and after. Photos, testimonials, income claims. She threw parties where nobody bought anything. She messaged old high school friends, trying to recruit them. People started avoiding her. By month six, we'd spent over $15,000 on products, training courses, and convention tickets. Jessica had made about $800 in actual sales. Most of that was from her mom buying stuff out of pity. I tried talking to her about cutting losses, but she'd get defensive. Said I didn't believe in her dreams, that I was comfortable being mediocre forever. One Saturday morning, Jessica had a complete breakdown at our kitchen table. She was crying over her laptop, looking at our bank account. We were down to $400, and our mortgage was due in three days. All the money we'd saved for a down payment on a bigger house was gone. Our emergency fund was empty. Jessica looked at me with tears streaming down her face and said she'd made a terrible mistake. I thought she meant the network marketing thing, but then she brought up that phone call. Said she'd been so focused on wanting a different life that she destroyed the good one we actually had. I told her I heard what she said to Amanda that day. About unsettling, about wanting more. Jessica's face went white. She tried to apologize, but I was honestly too tired to be angry anymore. I just asked her what she wanted to do now. She Said she wanted to fix things if I let her. Jessica got her old job back at the dental office. Took them two months, but they rehired her. She sold all that inventory at a garage sale for pennies on the dollar. We spent the next year digging ourselves out of debt, living on rice and beans. No vacations, no eating out, nothing extra. The kicker, though, her friend Amanda, the one she was always jealous of, got divorced last spring. Turns out all those vacation photos were funded by maxed out credit cards. Amanda's husband had been hiding their debt for years. They lost their house in the divorce. Meanwhile, Jessica's ex, Chris, the one with all the investment properties, got sued by his tenants for unsafe living conditions and lost two of his buildings. Just Jessica saw it on the news. We're doing okay now. Not rich, but stable. Jessica tells people she's grateful for her boring teacher husband who kept us from losing everything. I'm still not sure I've completely forgiven her for what she said. But I know she regrets more than just settling. She regrets almost throwing away something real for something that was never going to make her happy anyway.

My wife is telling her friend she regrets settling for me. Later, Karma hit her really hard. I was working from home when I heard my wife Jessica on the phone in the kitchen. I had my headphones on during a meeting, but my laptop died, and I went to grab the charger from the other room. That. That's when I heard her voice through the wall. She was talking to her friend Amanda, and I could tell from her tone. It was one of those deep conversation calls. I wasn't trying to eavesdrop, but then I heard my name. She said, I love David, but sometimes I wonder what my life would be like if I hadn't settled. I froze in the hallway. Amanda must have asked what she meant, because Jessica continued, like, he the good guy and everything, but he's a teacher. We're never going to be rich. Meanwhile, my ex boyfriend Chris, just bought his third investment property. My stomach dropped. I stood there like an idiot, listening to my wife of seven years tell her friend she regretted marrying me. She kept going. Amanda's always posting pictures from her vacations, and I'm over here clipping coupons. David's happy with his little life, but I wanted more. You know, I wanted the nice house and the fancy dinners and the lifestyle. I walked back to my office and sat there staring at the wall. That night at dinner, Jessica acted completely normal, asking about my day. Talking about her co workers, laughing at some TV show. The whole time, I kept hearing those words in my head. Settled little life. I didn't confront her because, honestly, what was I supposed to say? Two weeks later, Jessica came home excited about some network marketing opportunity. Her friend Tanya had recruited her to sell these wellness products. Jessica said, we can make six figures in our first year. She showed me spreadsheets and income projections. I had a bad feeling immediately, but she was so pumped up about it that I didn't want to crush her. Spent $3,000 on inventory that first month. Boxes of vitamins and shakes filled our garage. Jessica quit her job as a dental hygienist to focus on her business full time. She said she was finally going to build the life she deserved. I kept teaching and covering all our

Today, my best friend had a mental breakdown. He is my best friend, but I realized I was never his best friend. I've known Gary since sophomore year. We've been tight ever since. When my ex cheated on me two years ago and broke up with me, I completely fell apart. I stopped going out, stopped caring about anything, just stayed in my room playing video games for hours and honestly doing nothing productive. Gary saw what was happening and literally saved me. He bought me a gym membership with his own money, deleted every single distraction from my laptop and even drove me to therapy appointments every week for 3 months. When I was applying for jobs last year, he stayed up until 2 in the morning helping me practice interview questions. I have my current job because of him. Everyone wants to be around Gary. He's smart, always cracking jokes, always smiling. People at work, people from college, even random people at parties, they all gravitate toward him. Our whole friend group goes to him for advice. I've gone to him dozens of times. I've cried in front of him about my ex, about my mom being sick, about feeling lost. He always listens, always knows what to say. Yesterday, we were just hanging out at the park near his apartment. Nothing special, just sitting on a bench eating burgers from that food truck he likes. We were laughing about something stupid from work. Then suddenly he just Stopped talking. His whole face changed. He started crying, not like quiet tears, full on sobbing. Then he started hitting his own head with his hands, like actually hitting himself hard. I grabbed his arms and tried to hold him still.

There. A few nights ago, she cornered me while I was eating and said she hated our setup. She wanted me to start eating with her and the kids and split cooking duties with her. She kept saying we were a family and family should eat together. I told her we weren't a family and I didn't want to change anything. Then she brought up the baby and tried to use them as a reason for me to give it a shot. she genuinely thought I wanted a relationship with this random baby. Told her I didn't care about the baby at all. She wouldn't drop it, so I had to rush through my food and went up to my room. But she actually followed me upstairs and kept pushing the family dinner thing. Ever since that night, she brings it up constantly and tells me she's not happy I won't try. I think she went to my dad to get him to talk to me about it, but he told her to leave it alone because I'm not part of the family they're making. Even that didn't stop her, though. Last night, she was waiting for me when I got home at 5. She. I had this whole speech prepared about how it would mean so much to her kids if I ate with them, how the baby deserves to know their brother. I'm not anyone's brother. I told her that, and she actually started crying. She said She was just trying to make a real home for everyone, and I was making it impossible. I asked her why she even cared since she didn't know the first thing about me. She paused and then asked how old I was. I told her I'm 17. Her face went white because she thought I was already 19 or 20. She'd been living in the same house as me for a year and a half and didn't even know my age. That's when I finally lost it. I told her to stop pretending she cared about me or wanted me around. This was all about her wanting to play happy family, and I wasn't interested in being part of her fantasy. He left crying, and I heard her on the phone with someone later saying I was cold and mean. My dad hasn't said anything to me about it, which means he's staying out of it, like we agreed. But now she won't even look at me when I'm in the kitchen, and her kids stare at me like I'm some kind of monster.

I refuse to eat dinner with my dad's new wife and her kids, even though she kept begging me. I'm 17 and I only have my dad. My mom isn't around, and I don't have any other family I can live with. My relationship with my dad has always been non existent. He resented being stuck raising me alone and never wanted to be a father. When I was younger, I wanted us to be close so badly, but he made it clear he didn't want me as his kid. We don't even call each other dad and son. We use first names. A few years ago, we made this agreement that works for both of us. I don't bother him or ask him for anything, and he doesn't expect me to do chores or be part of his life. I buy and cook my own food, clean up after myself, and basically just sleep there. I moved into the guest room so I could have my own bathroom and privacy. Nobody goes near my room or my stuff. I used to babysit to make money for food and everything else I needed. The arrangement has worked perfectly for three years now. Then, about 18 months ago, my dad's girlfriend moved in with her three kids. They got married pretty fast and had a baby together. I wasn't invited to the wedding, and I don't know anything about her kids. Not their names, not their ages, nothing. I leave every Morning at 7 and come back around 5 to cook and eat my dinner alone in the kitchen. Then I leave again and come home around 8 and in my room. Usually I'm at my friend's house or the library doing homework. My dad doesn't get home until 7:30 or 8 most nights, so I never see him. His wife and her kids eat dinner earlier and she does all the cooking for them. I figured she didn't know about our agreement because she started coming home earlier and asking me weird questions like why was I eating alone and wouldn't I rather eat with everyone else? I always said no and ignored her so I could finish eating and get out of there.

My ex husband begged me to take him back at 2:00am because his mistress had just done to him what he did to me. My ex husband stood at my door at 2:00am sobbing uncontrollably about how his mistress had betrayed him. The same man who'd laughed when I cried about our marriage ending wanted my sympathy now. Eight months ago, my husband Trevor left me for his 26 year old yoga instructor, Jack Jasmine. We've been married 12 years, built a successful catering business. I discovered their affair through our iPad when her intimate photos synced during dinner. When confronted, Trevor blamed me, said I'd let myself go after our twins were born, that Jasmine made him feel alive and understood his need for adventure. He filed for divorce immediately, demanding I buy out his business, half or sell everything. Fought for fifty fifty custody just to reduce child support. Posted photos with Jasmine at the Maldives resort. While I was getting served divorce papers, my nine year old twins kept asking why daddy's new friend wore mommy's jewelry on Instagram. He'd been gifting her pieces from my grandmother's collection he'd claimed were lost during our move. The divorce was brutal. Trevor hired the most aggressive lawyer in town, claiming I'd been emotionally abusive by controlling his friendships. He got the house since it was his inheritance property, though I'd spent three years renovating it. I moved into a townhouse with the kids, kept the catering business running solo. While he collected monthly buyout payments, Jasmine immediately moved in, redecorated everything, and started a lifestyle blog about creating your dream space with your soulmate. She actually tagged me, thanking me for letting Trevor find true happiness. For months, I focused on rebuilding, doubled my catering contracts, started teaching cooking classes, even went on a few dates. Then last Tuesday, someone's pounding my door at 2:00am. Through the doorbell camera, I see Trevor absolutely wrecked, tears streaming. Against better judgment, I opened with the chain on. He immediately launched into his pathetic story. Jasmine had been cheating for four months with her Crossfit trainer, Antonio. But here's the beautiful part. She'd been using Trevor's money to fund Antonio's new gym and told Antonio that Trevor was just her sugar daddy, too.

Jim, but Herbert knew Leo was going to dump you, Jeff added, so he was ready to talk to Leo about dating you. I felt like I was going to throw up. What do you mean talk? They made a deal, Jeff said quietly. Remember the business trip Leo went on in August? Well, Leo's still there. He never came back. It was all a boy for Herbert to enter your life. You picked up Herbert from the airport that day and have been with him ever since. The room was spin. After that trip, my boyfriend had been different. He became less confident, quieter. He'd forgotten our inside jokes. His kiss was different. The way he touched me was completely different. Like he was trying to figure out what I liked from scratch. I thought he was just acting weird because he was stressed from work, I whispered. Well, you were wrong. He was acting differently because it was a completely different person. Jess said. Herbert was learning how to be your boyfriend, learning what you liked, trying to copy Leo's personality, but failing because he's now truly shy and anxious. For two and a/2 years, my voice cracked. I've been with a different person for two and a/2 years and no one told me. We thought you knew. Just said miserably. They're twins. We assumed you figured it out and we're okay with it. maybe you preferred Herbert's personality once you got to know him. Their friends all know. Just added. Their parents know. Everyone at their gym knows Leo thinks it's hilarious. He brags about how his brother Herbert got his sloppy seconds and you couldn't even tell. I stood up again, grabbing the table because it felt like the world was crumbling around me. I fell in love with Leo. I was in love with Leo. But you've been sleeping with Herbert, Jess said quietly. You've been engaged to her, Herbert. Tomorrow you're marrying Herbert. My phone rang. It was Herbert. I answered on the fifth ring and he spoke first. Hey, babe, how's the party? His voice was warm, a little drunk. In the background, I heard someone jokingly shout, tell her Leo loves her. And a bunch of guys laughing. I hung up without saying anything. The truth was suffocating me. Every moment for the past two and a half years had been a lie. It was with the wrong twin, the boring twin who needed his brother's personality to get me. I left the party and went straight to Instagram. I found their family page and messaged their dad, their really hot dad who'd always stared at me at family reunions. I messaged him, are you free tonight? Long story short, we spent the night together and their dad, Gerbert, was better than both twins combined. No cap.

World. He had a little sister named Fenn who was my best friend. I wanted to tell him. My gut instinct told me what Natasha was doing was bad, but I was terrified. Terrified I'd lose my family over a guitar string. Then Fenn texted me, O m. G, Alexander is flying back this weekend to surprise Natasha. He wants you to help. We're picking him up from the airport Saturday and surprising her together. My hands started shaking. Saturday, that was the day Natasha told me Baylor was coming again. I texted back, hey, but I felt like I was going to throw up all week. I couldn't sleep. Saturday came. Natasha reminded me that morning, Baylor's coming at 2. Don't tell anyone. At noon, Ben and I picked up Alexander from the airport, got in the car grinning. I can't wait to see her face. She has no idea. I was sitting in the back seat, my hands and fists. Alexander kept talking. I missed her so much. I've been thinking about this for weeks. I couldn't breathe. Alexander glanced in the rearview mirror. You okay? Back there. I started crying. I couldn't, can't hold it anymore. I have to tell you something. Alexander pulled over. I told him everything. The guitar, the blackmail, Baylor coming over multiple times today. The car was silent. Alexander's hands were gripping the steering wheel. His voice was quiet. My best friend Ben was staring at me, then at her brother. Are You. Her voice was small. Are you going to fly back home? Alexander's face suddenly changed. Fly back? Hell no. He looked at both of us, confronting them. Right now, you two want to join me? We squealed. Our first stop was a party store. Alexander walked straight to the costume section, grabbed two clown masks. If they want to act like clowns, let's make it official. Then found confetti cannons. I grabbed party streamers that said congratulations. We drove to my house. I unlocked the front door. We walked upstairs in complete silence. I could hear voices in Natasha's room. Alexander didn't knock. He kicked the door open, blasted an airhorn. Natasha and Baylor jumped apart. We were standing there, three people dressed for a Celebration. Surprise, babe. Natasha's face went white. Alexander, how did you. Baylor was frozen. Dude, I can explain. Alexander walked up to Natasha, put the clown mask on her head. Since you want to act like a clown, Ben put her mask on. Baylor, I shot the confetti cannon. Congratulations on being terrible people. Confetti everywhere. Natasha ripped the mask off screaming. She pointed at me. You told them? Yeah, I did. I'm telling dad about the guitar. Alexander stepped between us. You've been blackmailing an 11 year old. She opened her mouth but nothing came out. Her face went red. Embarrassed, she looked at me and out of nowhere lunged. But Alexander blocked her. Touch her and we'll press charges. Baylor tried to Leave, but Fenn blocked the door. You're staying for this? We made them stay while Alexander recorded a video of them trying to hide under the sheets. Everyone cut them off. I eventually told dad about the guitar. He laughed. I was going to replace those anyway.

My sister blackmailed me into being her cover story. In the end, she realised she was only manipulating herself. When I was 11, I picked up my dad's guitar and strummed the strings. It sounded cool, but I wanted it louder. So I strummed again really hard. This time the thinnest string snapped and hit my face. My stomach dropped. I stared at the broken string hanging limp, holding my my cheek. I started tearing up. That's when my 17 year old sister Natasha appeared in the doorway. Oh my god. Her voice was sharp. You broke Dad's guitar. I didn't mean to. He's going to freak out. She stepped closer. You know how he is about his guitar. He'll disown. Tears filled my eyes. I'm sorry. He's going to send you to the bad children home, she interrupted. You won't see us ever again. I started crying. That's when her face changed. But I won't tell him. My eyes lit up. Thank you. Thank you. Best sis. You're the best. She hugged me. But you have to do something for me in return. I pulled back. Anything. She smiled. Perfect. Someone's going to be coming to our house in an hour. Promise you won't tell anyone who? I was confused. Who's coming over doesn't matter. Do you promise or not? My heart was pounding. I promise. She smiled. Good girl. An hour later, there was a knock at the door. I opened it. Taylor was standing there. My sister's Boyfriend's best friend. Hey, he looked past me. Is Natasha here? I let him in. My stomach felt weird. They went upstairs to her room. I sat on the couch trying to understand why Alexander's best friend was here, why Natasha didn't want me to tell him. An hour later, they came down. Her hair was ruffled. Baylor left without saying much. I found Natasha in the kitchen. Why was Baylor here? She was getting water. What do you mean? Does Alexander know? Of course he knows. It's fine. But it didn't feel fine. Then why did you tell me not to tell anyone if Alexander knows? She turned to face me. Because mom and dad don't like people over when they're not home, so don't say anything to anyone. I wanted to ask more questions, but she was looking at me hard. Remember the guitar? I gulped and nodded. Baylor came over three more times over the next month. Each time, Natasha blackmailed me. I felt sick every time, especially because Alexander was perfect. He visit our family. He was nice to me. Asked about school, treated Natasha like she was the only girl in the.

At my bachelorette party, my maid of honor announced, I can't believe you've been with two twin brothers from the same family! I almost spit out my champagne laughing. What twin brothers? I asked. I've only been with Leo, my fiance, and he doesn't have any siblings. The entire table went silent. Everyone was looking at each other with these panicked expressions, like they knew something I didn't. You mean Leo and Herbert, my maid of honor, Jess said slowly. Your fiance and his identical twin brother. My stomach dropped. Who the hell is Herbert? Leo doesn't have any siblings. My sister grabbed Jess's arm and whispered for her to shut up, but I was already waiting for answers. Someone better explain what's going going on right now. They all kept looking at each other, trying to figure out who should talk. Finally, my friend sighed. Jess, just tell her everything, since you already started the explanation. Jess took a huge drink of her wine first. Okay, so in spring 2021, during a rooftop party, you met a guy there, right? Yeah, I met Leo, my fiance. I said, no, that wasn't Leo. It was Leo. Identical twin brother, Herbert. A twin that you never knew about? My legs felt so weak with shock that I had to sit back down. That's impossible! My husband is an only child. Just listen, Jessa. The guy you met at that party was Herbert's twin brother, Leo. Leo was the confident one, the Charming one. My hands were shaking. Now you're telling me that wasn't Herbert? Herbert is the shy twin, Jess continued. But from the moment Leo brought you around, Herbert was obsessed with you. He'd watch you guys from a distance, just waiting for you to break up so he could swoop in and be with you instead. This is insane, I said. But they kept going. By August 2,021, Leo was done with you. Just said. It's what he does. He dates girls for a few months until he gets bored, then ghost them. He was already talking to some girl from his

Greg that night that something was off. He said his mom was just anxious about the baby and trying to help. He asked me to give her a break, so I did. The next morning, I woke up to voices downstairs. Diane was on the phone talking to someone. I heard her say my name, so I stopped on the stairs to listen. She was telling whoever it was that I wasn't eating enough and the baby was measuring small, both lies. She said Greg was worried about me but didn't know how to say it, also a lie. Then she said maybe they should consider taking the baby after it was born because I clearly wasn't stable enough to be a mother. She said my anxiety medication proved I had mental problems. I walked down and asked who she was talking to. She hung up fast and said it was her sister. I asked why she was lying about me. She said she wasn't lying and that I was being paranoid. I told her to get out of my house. She refused and she promised Greg she'd take care of me and she wasn't leaving. I called Greg at work and told him what happened. He came home early. Diane told him I was being hormonal and irrational. She actually used those words. Greg asked what the phone call was about. She said I was making it up. I grabbed her phone off the counter and opened her recent Calls. The last one was to Child Protective Services. I just stared at the screen. She'd actually called CPS on me while living in my house. Greg lost it, started yelling at her, asking what she was thinking. Diane said she was protecting her grandchild from an unfit mother. She brought up the medication again and said I'd been acting erratic. Greg told her to pack her stuff and leave. She tried arguing, but he wasn't hearing it. She packed up crying and saying we'd regret this. She was only trying to help. She left and I just sat there shaking. Two days later, a CPS worker showed up. Someone had filed a report claiming I was abusing drugs and planning to neglect the baby. They interviewed me and Greg checked the house, looked at my medical records. The whole thing was humiliating. The worker figured out pretty quick it was bogus and closed the case. But it's on file now forever.

My mother in law is dead to me for what she did. My husband Greg and I got married three years ago. His mom, Diane, seemed cool at first. She helped with the wedding and everything. We moved two hours away from my job and visited maybe once a month, normal stuff. Last year, I got pregnant. We told everyone at 12 weeks, Diane cried happy tears and hugged me. She kept texting me asking about doctor appointments and if I needed anything. Thought she was just excited to be a grandma. At 7 months, I went into early labor. The doctor stopped it but put me on bed rest. Greg had to go back to work after a week, so Diane offered to stay with me. She took time off her job and drove down with like four suitcases. I figured she was just being helpful. First few days were fine. She made food and did laundry. But then I noticed she kept going through my stuff. I caught her in our bedroom closet one morning looking through boxes. She said she was looking for extra blankets. Okay, whatever. Then my pills started going missing. I had anxiety medication I've been taking for years. The bottle was in the bathroom cabinet and suddenly half of them were gone. I asked Diane if she'd seen them. She said no and helped me look. We never found them. I had to call my doctor for an early refill. We 2 she Started getting weird about the nursery. We'd set it up before the bed rest and she kept saying we did it wrong. The crib was in the wrong spot. The changing table was too close to the window. She moved stuff around when I was sleeping. Greg told her to stop, but she said she knew better since she'd raised two kids. Then I found her going through my phone. I'd left it charging in the kitchen and walked in on her scrolling through my messages. She jumped and said she thought it was hers. Her phone was literally in her hand. I told.

voice_to_text: Before she asked him if he used the right milk, he started laughing and told her what he did. She got really mad, started yelling at him about how he knows she doesn't consume animal products, how it's not just a preference but something she cares about. He kept saying it was just a joke and she was overreacting. That's why he asked me to meet him outside instead of going to the house. She told him she didn't want to see him for the rest of the day. Dad looked at me across the table and said, that's funny, right? Like he wanted me to agree with him, to laugh about it. I just sat there for a second. Then I pulled a face and said, don't think so, dad, because I really couldn't see how it was funny. His whole expression changed. He looked annoyed, maybe even angry. He said people these days can't take a joke anymore, that everyone's too sensitive. Then he said, I'm his son and I'm supposed to side with him, that I shouldn't be judgmental since it was harmless, just milk and coffee, no big deal. I told him it wasn't harmless, though. She's vegan for a reason. He made her consume something she specifically avoids on purpose just to mess with her. He waved his hand like I was being dramatic, said it's not like she's allergic, it's just a choice. I said, yeah, it's her choice. And he ignored it to Prank her. He got quiet after that, finished his coffee without looking at me. Then he said, I've changed that I used to laugh at his jokes when I was younger. I told him I was a kid then I didn't really get that his pranks upset people. Now I'm older and I can see when something's mean instead of funny. He didn't like that answer. We left the cafe 20 minutes later, dropped me off at Mom's house early. Didn't even come inside. Just said, see you next week and drove off. When I got inside, mom asked why I was back so soon. I told her what happened. She shook her head and said, your dad never grew up. Some people think pranks are a personality trait instead of just being annoying.

How did you convince 80 teenagers to break into your principal's house at midnight? My grandfather wasn't just Westfield High's principal, he was its beating heart. He'd show up to Spirit Week in full costume, lose his voice at Pep rallies and turn senior pranks into legendary battles he somehow always won. The man literally orchestrated a midnight operation to relocate every senior desk onto the football field after they flipped his office upside down. But when we lost grandma last spring, we lost him too. He'd become the complete opposite. No more costumes, no more jokes, and definitely no more pranks. When my classmates started buzzing about senior prank ideas in March, he shut it down immediately over the morning announcements. There will be no senior prank this year. Any student caught attempting one will not walk at graduation. This is non negotiable. Everyone kept coming up to me in the hallways. Josh, you have to talk to him. Come on, you're his grandson. He'll listen to you. But I already tried. Every Sunday dinner at his empty house, I'd watch him push food around his plate in that too quiet kitchen where grandma used to hum while cooking. He'd just grunt when I mentioned school traditions. Rules are rules, Josh, even for you. My friends were relentless, though. During lunch, everyone kept begging me to come up with something. That's when I remembered this hilarious TikTok I'd seen where an entire senior class snuck into their principal's house. For a sleepover, just camping out in sleeping bags until he woke up. It was wholesome, harmless, and honestly, kind of sweet. I looked around the table, guys, what if we all broke into his house for a sleepover? The planning was intricate, but everyone was committed to pulling this off perfectly. I still had a spare key from when I used to stay over as a kid. And I knew my grandfather's routine by heart. He always took his hearing aid out at night and slept like a rock until his 6 a. M. Alarm. We wouldn't damage anything or steal anything. We'd just be 80 seniors with sleeping bags having the world's quietest slumber party in his living room and kitchen. I knew every creek in that house, every security light, even which windows he never locked. Midnight on April 30th, I LED the entire senior class through his backyard. We moved like ninjas, carrying sleeping bags and pillows, suppressing giggles as we filed through the back door. Everyone was so careful and respectful. We laid out our sleeping bags in perfect rows, took selfies, giving.

My girlfriend's dad shook my hand at the grocery store and said, congratulations, son, you're doing the right thing. I had no idea what he meant. I was picking up milk for my mom when I ran into Mister Barry in the cereal aisle, Katie's dad. We'd only met once before, briefly when I picked her up for homecoming. He saw me and his whole face lit up. Walked straight over with his huge smile. Evan, just the young man I wanted to see. He shook my hand, firm grip. Congratulations, son. You're doing the right thing. Katie's mother and I were really proud of you. I stood there holding a Alan of milk, completely confused. Uh, thank you. Your parents must be thrilled, too. My mom appeared behind me with the shopping cart. Thrilled about what? Mr Barry's smile faltered. Oh, you haven't told them yet? Told them what? He shifted uncomfortably. I think I should let Katie explain. But really, congratulations. You're being very mature about this. He walked away fast. My mom looked at me. What was that about? I have no idea. I pulled out my phone and called Katie straight to voicemail. Texted, what is your dad talking about? No response. Evan, what's going on, mom? I seriously don't know. That night my phone rang. Katie's mom, hi, Missus Barry, Evan, honey, I just wanted to say how mature you're being about all this. My head was spinning. About what long pause? Katie hasn't talked. To you yet. Talk to me about what I think you two need to have a conversation. I'll have her call you. She hung up. I tried Katie again. Voicemail. I texted, your mom just called. What is going on? No response. My phone wouldn't stop buzzing. Katie's mom, Katie's dad, my own parents asking questions I could answer. By Monday morning, I was losing my mind. My mom came into my room. Katie's mother just called me. What did she say? She said you and Katie made a very important decision together that we should be proud of how you're handling it. Evan, what decision, mom? I swear, I don't know. Is Katie okay? I don't know. She won't answer her phone. That night, Doug showed up at my door. Bro, my mom just told me about you and Katie. That's crazy. You good? I pulled him inside. What did your mom tell you? Just that you guys are dealing with some serious stuff. She wouldn't give details, but he looked uncomfortable. You sure this is what you want, Doug? I have no idea what anyone is talking about. His eyes widened. Wait, you seriously don't know? No, dude, you need to find Katie. This sounds big. The next morning, I went to Katie's house before school, knocked on the door. Katie's mom answered. Her eyes were red. Evan, she doesn't want to see you right now. Why not? What's happening? She's going through a lot. Give her some Space, Missus, Barry, please. Nobody will tell me what's going on. She looked at me for a long moment. You really don't know? No.

At my wedding rehearsal dinner, my mother stood up and announced, we're not paying for the circus. She picked the wrong man. My fiance and I exchanged glances. I replied, perfect and got security to kick her out. The same night she texted, don't forget the mortgage payment and the Tesla car loan payments are tomorrow. I stared at that text until my hands stopped shaking. On read over my shoulder, what mortgage? What Tesla? That's when six years of lies came pouring out. When I was 22, my mother called crying, dad made bad investments. They'd lose the house. Could I help just temporarily? I co signed a 60 thousand dollar mortgage refinance.
